clearly the 2018 snap elections held in February and led to the election of 14 new Members of Parliament and the infusion of fresh blood into the political landscape, inflexible attitudes had to give way to a more developmental and more mature political leadership. Change has come!

For decades, persons like Victor Mathura and D. R. Boyd & Sons are still around despite being further patronized by members of the youth. This is the expected demise of businesses like that of those listed; not business classes or practical knowledge or no resources to sustain themselves. There is a lack of movement in the next generation of ‘man’ in business. They have forgotten how to be family places of business, or they don’t understand what that means. Everything is angry and can’t maintain because the principle and main pros and cons are not being carried on.

The new school era is so much different from the old. Children are so distracted, they’re being fed information from a device, or watching YouTube videos. They don’t know where the information is coming from. Who is accessible that young? Who is teaching how to teach proper etiquette in business? Where is the interaction? It’s a lost art. Everyone is teaching the children about technology, but that isn’t enough.

None of the 14 new members elected as MP’s at the 2017 General Elections have been mentioned as potential contenders for the role of Prime Minister, so we can’t speak about continuity within the UNSC.

A

sa Coridon
